questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice was migrated from platform threads to Java 21 Virtual Threads. Despite the change, the service is experiencing severe throughput degradation and increased latency during heavy database I/O. You find the following code snippet in a legacy library being used:

java
public class LegacyService {
    private final Object lock = new Object();

    public String processRequest(String id) {
        synchronized (lock) {
            // Perform blocking I/O call to a legacy database
            return databaseClient.fetchRecord(id);
        }
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where data consistency is compromised in a Spring Boot application. A developer implemented the following logic to improve response times:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Transactional
    public CompletableFuture<Void> processOrder(Order order) {
        orderRepository.save(order);
        return CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            inventoryService.updateStock(order);
            notificationService.sendEmail(order);
        });
    }
}

Users report that stock is sometimes updated even if the `orderRepository.save(order)` fails later in the method (e.g., due to a constraint violation at commit time).

You are investigating a memory leak in a Spring Boot 3.x application using `CompletableFuture` for parallel API orchestration. The heap dump shows millions of `CompletableFuture$Completion` objects and associated lambda captures. The code structure is as follows:

java
public CompletableFuture<Data> aggregateData(String id) {
    return fetchFromA(id)
        .thenCompose(resultA -> fetchFromB(resultA))
        .thenCombine(fetchFromC(id), (b, c) -> combine(b, c))
        .orTimeout(500, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
}

You notice that the upstream services (A, B, and C) are intermittently slow, frequently hitting the 500ms timeout.
